Operations in OX Documents Applications

Operations are used to transfer the document data from the server to the client (opening a document) and from the client to the server (saving changes made during editing a document). Operations are a prerequirement for collaborative working on a document.

Please notice: This is for demonstration purpose only. Operations in OX Documents can change anytime. They are not meant to be a public API. We have meanwhile shortened operation names and attributes to limit bandwidth usage, so they are no longer so nicely readable like documented below.

Data Types

Property values in operations may consist of complex objects instead of simple values (strings, numbers). The following chapters define the contents of these complex values. The chapter title contains the type name as used in the remaining documentation.

Position

A value of type Position describes the exact position of a specific component in the document. A position is always an array of non-negative integer values. The exact meaning of the array elements is dependent on the operation, or even on the application that uses a generic operation.

LineHeight

The total height of a text line, either absolute, or relative to the font size of the text in the line.

Property Data Type Default Value Description
type Enum percent Type of the line height. See table below for details.
value Integer 100 Length value (1/100mm or percent), depending on the type property. See table below for details.
LineHeight type LineHeight value
percent Line height, in percent of the normal line height. The normal line height is dependent on the font face and font size (usually somewhere between 110% and 140% of the font size).
fixed Fixed line height, in 1/100 mm.
leading Spacing between lines in 1/100 mm, will be added to 100% line height.
atLeast Fixed minimum line height in 1/100 mm, will be used if larger than 100% line height.

TabStop

Defines a tab stop inside a paragraph.

Property Data Type Default Value Description
fillChar Enum none Type of fill character.
none Tab is just empty space.
dot Tab will be filled with dot chars: . . . . . . . . . . .
hyphen Tab will be filled with hyphen chars: - - - - - - - - -
underscore Tab will be filled with underscore chars _ _ _ _ _ _ _
pos Integer 0 Tab stop position in 1/100th mm.
value Enum left Type of justification for the tab stop.
left Following text is located right of the tab stop (text is left-aligned to the tab stop).
center Following text is located centered around the tab stop.
right Following text is located left of the tab stop (text is right-aligned to the tab stop).
decimal Following text with decimal separator will be aligned so the decimal separator is located at the tab stop position.
bar A vertical line is painted exactly at the position of the tab stop. This position won't change by a text input absolute position.
clear Removes a tab stop from the current tab stop list. Can be used to remove a previously defined tab stop in a parent style sheet.

DrawingPosition

The position of a drawing object is a Position array whose contents are dependent on the document type.

  • See the definition of a text drawing position for text documents in OX Text.
  • See the definition of a sheet drawing position for spreadsheet documents in OX Spreadsheet.

EmbeddedDrawingPosition

The positions of drawing objects embedded in other drawing objects (supported by groups and charts only) are built by extending the DrawingPosition of the parent drawing object with the zero-based index of the embedded drawing object among all child drawings of the parent drawing object.

  • Example: A group object at position [0,4] contains three child objects with the indexes 0, 1, and 2. These child drawing objects are located at the positions [0,4,0], [0,4,1], and [0,4,2] then.

Drawing objects can be nested recursively.

  • Example: A group object at position [0,4] contains a nested group object at position [0,4,0] which contains a chart at position [0,4,0,0].

Color

Description of a color value. Colors may be defined by a simple RGB value, or may refer to scheme colors defined by a document theme (inserted with the operation "insertTheme").

Property Data Type Default Value Description
type Enum auto Color type, affects the value property. See table below for details.
value String | Object Color value, depends on type property. See table below for details.
transformations Array<ColorTransformation> [] Transformations to be applied to the initial color value.
fallbackValue String 6-digits upper-case hexadecimal string (RRGGBB). This color should be used whenever a system is not able to calculate a color value from the type+value+transformation pair. Especially needed by systems which don't support theming or transformations.

Depending on the color type, the color values have different meanings:

Color type Color value Data Type Color value Notes
rgb String RGB color model, 6-digits upper-case hexadecimal string (RRGGBB).
hsl Object HSL color model, as object with the properties h (hue), s (saturation), and l (luminance). Hue must be in the interval [0,21599999], saturation and luminance must be in the interval [0,100000].
crgb Object CRGB color model, each color channel as percentage, as object with the properties r (red), g (green), and b (blue). Each value must be in the interval [0,100000]. (1)
scheme String Case-sensitive scheme color name from current theme.
system String Name of a system color. The effective color value depends on the environment.
preset String Name of a predefined color.
auto Not used The effective color value depends on the context.
Text characters May depend on the current background color (character/paragraph) which must be calculated by the client, therefore the backend should NOT set any fixed color here.
Border lines Usually black. May be a different color, e.g. in spreadsheet documents where the automatic border color equals the grid line color.
Background fill Usually transparent, or any predefined color or calculated color depending on the context, e.g. in chart objects.

Notes:

1) The CRGB color model uses linear values for the color channels (without gamma correction). When converting from CRGB color model to RGB or HSL color model, a gamma transformation (see ColorTransformation) must be applied implicitly to the resulting color.

The following constants will be used in this documentation:

Constant Name Definition
Color.AUTO {type:auto}

ColorTransformation

Color transformations are contained in Color values, and modify the base color defined by the color value. Each transformation object contains the following properties:

Property Type Default Description
type Enum ColorTransformationType required Type of the color transformation.
value Integer 0 Value, depends on the transformation type attribute. See ColorTransformationType for details.

ColorTransformationType

Specifies how to transform a given color. The following variables will be used in the following descriptions:

Variable Value Range Description
R [0,100000] Red channel (RGB color model).
G [0,100000] Green channel (RGB color model).
B [0,100000] Blue channel (RGB color model).
H [0,21599999] Hue channel (HSL color model). 0: red (0deg); 7200000: green (120deg); 14400000: blue (240deg).
S [0,100000] Saturation channel (HSL color model). 0: gray; 100000: full color.
L [0,100000] Luminance channel (HSL color model). 0: black; 50000: color; 100000: white.
A [0,100000] Opacity (alpha channel). 0: transparent; 100000: opaque.

The following table will describe how to modify the components of the color for each transformation type:

Enum Value Value Range Value Description Color Model Implementation Notes Notes
alpha [0,100000] Sets the opaqueness of the color. By default, the color is fully opaque. 0: transparent; 100000: opaque. RGB/HSL Anew = value
alphaMod [0,*] Modulates the opaqueness of the color. The value 100000 leaves opacity unmodified. RGB/HSL Anew = A * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,100000]
alphaOff [-100000,100000] Shifts the opaqueness of the color. The value 0 leaves opacity unmodified. RGB/HSL Anew = A + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
red [0,100000] Sets the red channel of the color. RGB Rnew = value
redMod [0,*] Modulates the red channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Rnew = R * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,100000]
redOff [-100000,100000] Shifts the red channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Rnew = R + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
green [0,100000] Sets the green channel of the color. RGB Gnew = value
greenMod [0,*] Modulates the green channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Gnew = G + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
greenOff [-100000,100000] Shifts the green channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Gnew = G + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
blue [0,100000] Sets the green channel of the color. RGB Gnew = value
blueMod [0,*] Modulates the blue channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Bnew = B * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,100000]
blueOff [-100000,100000] Shifts the blue channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Bnew = B + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
hue [0,21599999] Sets the hue channel of the color. HSL Hnew = value
hueMod [0,*] Modulates the hue channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Hnew = H * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,21599999]
hueOff [-21599999,21599999] Shifts the hue channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Hnew = H + value, result restricted to interval [0,21599999]
sat [0,100000] Sets the saturation channel of the color. HSL Snew = value
satMod [0,*] Modulates the saturation channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Snew = S * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,100000]
satOff [-100000,100000] Shifts the saturation channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Snew = S + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
lum [0,100000] Sets the luminance channel of the color. HSL Lnew = value (1)
lumMod [0,*] Modulates the luminance channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Lnew = L * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,100000] (1)
lumOff [-100000,100000] Shifts the luminance channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Lnew = L + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000] (1)
shade [0,100000] Darkens the color. 0: black; 100000: original color. RGB RGBnew = RGB * (value/100000) (2)
tint [0,100000] Lightens the color. 0: white; 100000: original color. RGB RGBnew = (RGB-100000) * (value/100000) + 100000 (2)
comp not used Complement color (rotate hue by 180 degrees). HSL Hnew = (H + 10800000) mod 21600000
inv not used Inverse color (color channels inversed). RGB RGBnew = 100000 - RGB (2)
gamma not used Gamma correction (increases luminance of medium light colors). RGB RGBnew = (RGB/100000)1/2.27 * 100000 (2)
invGamma not used Inversed gamma correction (decreases luminance of medium light colors). RGB RGBnew = (RGB/100000)2.27 * 100000 (2)
gray not used Monochrome color. RGB RGBnew = 0.22 * R + 0.72 * G + 0.06 * B (2)

Notes

(1) If a luminance transformation results in the luminance values 0 or 100000, additionally the saturation of the color must be set to 0.

(2) Must be applied to all three color channels R, G, and B.

Property Type Default Description

Gradient

Description of a color gradient. A color gradient is the transition in between at least 2 colors.

Property Data Type Default Value Description
type Enum linear Specifies one of the two possible gradient-fill main-types:
linear This gradient fill is of gradient type linear. Linear gradient type means that the transition from one color to the next is along a line (e.g. horizontal, vertical, diagonal, etc.).
path This gradient fill is of gradient type path. Path gradient type means the that the boundary of transition from one color to the next is defined by e.g. a circle, a rectangle or a freely formed shape.
pathType Enum shape Specifies one of the 3 possible gradient-fill path sub-types:
circle same as pathType=rect
rect The gradient follows a rectangular path. This rectangular path sub-type is defined by its 4 additional edge attributes top, bottom, left and right describing the shading rectangle for a centered gradient relatively to the fill tile rectangle. Thus the shade does fill the entire tile except for the margins specified by those edge attributes. Each edge of the center shade rectangle is defined by a percentage offset from the corresponding edge of the tile rectangle. A positive percentage specifies an inset, while a negative percentage specifies an outset.
shape The gradient follows its shape.
left Double 0 Values from (including) -1 to 1. Specifies in percentage format (from the left to the right) the position of the left edge of the center shade rectangle. 0 targets the left edge of this rectangle whereas 1 targets its right edge.
right Double 0 Values from (including) -1 to 1. Specifies in percentage format (from the right to the left) the position of the right edge of the center shade rectangle. 0 targets the right edge of this rectangle whereas 1 targets its left edge.
top Double 0 Values from (including) -1 to 1. Specifies in percentage format (from the top to the bottom) the position of the top edge of the center shade rectangle. 0 targets the top edge of this rectangle whereas 1 targets its bottom edge.
bottom Double 0 Values from (including) -1 to 1. Specifies in percentage format (from the bottom to the top) the position of the bottom edge of the center shade rectangle. 0 targets the bottom edge of this rectangle whereas 1 targets its top edge.
pathFillLeft Double 0.5 Values from (including) -1 to 1. Specifies in percentage format (from the left to the right) the position of the left edge of the center shade rectangle. 0 targets the left edge of this rectangle whereas 1 targets its right edge.
pathFillRight Double 0.5 Values from (including) -1 to 1. Specifies in percentage format (from the right to the left) the position of the right edge of the center shade rectangle. 0 targets the right edge of this rectangle whereas 1 targets its left edge.
pathFillTop Double 0.5 Values from (including) -1 to 1. Specifies in percentage format (from the top to the bottom) the position of the top edge of the center shade rectangle. 0 targets the top edge of this rectangle whereas 1 targets its bottom edge.
pathFillBottom Double 0.5 Values from (including) -1 to 1. Specifies in percentage format (from the bottom to the top) the position of the bottom edge of the center shade rectangle. 0 targets the bottom edge of this rectangle whereas 1 targets its top edge.
rotation Double 0 Specifies the direction of color change for the gradient (indicating its orientation - e.g. vertical, horizontal, diagonal). A floating number range with values from (including) 0 to (excluding) 360.
isRotateWithShape Boolean false A flag that indicates whether a gradient will rotate with its shape.
isScaled Boolean false Specifies whether a gradient angle scales with the fill region or not.
flipH Boolean false Specifies if the gradient is mirrored horrizontally.
flipV Boolean false Specifies if the gradient is mirrored vertically.
colorStops Array<ColorStop> [] A list of color stops specifying the distribution of colors along the gradient.

Formatting Attributes

Formatting attributes are used to modify the appearance of a specific component in the document. An object of type Attributes contains a variable number of attribute values, mapped by the attribute name. An attribute value can be an atomic value, an array, or an object of any type described above.

The following chapters describe all generic formatting attributes, divided by their attribute type. Unless specified differently, the values of all measurement attributes (sizes, margins, indentations, etc.) are in 1/100 of millimeters.

Attribute Scope

The scope of an attribute describes where this attribute can occur:

Scope Description
element The attribute can be set explicitly at a component with an inserting or modifying operation. Additionally, a global default value may be specified with the setDocumentAttributes operation.
style The attribute can be inserted into a style sheet with the insertStyleSheet operation.
all The attribute can be set explicitly at a component, and can be inserted into a style sheet with the insertStyleSheet operation.

DocumentAttributes

Applications all
Attribute type document

These attributes are only supported in the setDocumentAttributes operation.

Attribute Data Type Default Value Application Description
fileFormat Enum ooxml all The file format type this document is based on. The functionality of the applications may be depending on the underlying file format.
ooxml Office Open XML (native format of Microsoft Office).
odf Open Document Format (native format of Apache Open Office, LibreOffice).

The different applications may define more specific document attributes which will be described in the respective articles.

PageAttributes

Applications all
Attribute type page

Page formatting attributes will be applied to page elements.

Attribute Data Type Default Value Scope Description Notes
width Integer 0 all Page width, including all margins.
height Integer 0 all Page height, including all margins.
orientation Enum portrait all Page orientation (one of portrait, landscape). This is NOT supported in OX Presentation.
marginLeft Integer 0 all Distance from the left page border to the left border of the content area.
marginRight Integer 0 all Distance from the right page border to the right border of the content area.
marginTop Integer 0 all Distance from the top page border to the top border of the content area. (1)
marginBottom Integer 0 all Distance from the bottom page border to the bottom border of the content area. (1)
marginHeader Integer 0 all Distance from the top page border to the top border of the header.
marginFooter Integer 0 all Distance from the bottom page border to the bottom border of the footer.
firstPage Boolean false all Whether to use separate header/footer settings for the first page.
evenOddPages Boolean false all Whether to use separate header/footer settings for even and odd pages, and mirror margin settings accordingly.
Notes

(1) The top and bottom page margin will include a header or footer if existing. If the header/footer is too large to fit into the empty space, the effective size of the page content area has to be reduced to prevent the header/footer from overlapping with the page content area.

ImageAttributes

Applications all
Attribute type image

Formatting attributes for images and OLE objects.

Attribute Data Type Default Value Scope Description Notes
imageUrl String "" element URL pointing to the image data. If the image is embedded in the document, the URL will be relative to the document (e.g. images/img1.png). (1)
imageData String "" element Image data. The string contains either Base64 image data, or SVG mark-up. If Base64 encoded image data is used, the string begins with data: otherwise if SVG is used it begins with <svg. (1)
cropLeft Number 0 all Cropping size on the left side of the bitmap. (2)
cropRight Number 0 all Cropping size on the right side of the bitmap. (2)
cropTop Number 0 all Cropping size on the upper side of the bitmap. (2)
cropBottom Number 0 all Cropping size on the lower side of the bitmap. (2)
Notes

(1) The attributes imageUrl and imageData are mutually exclusive.

  • An exception to this rule was introduced for the clipboard handling. The copy handler can not decide whether the imageUrl or the imageData attribute is needed on paste. Therefore the copy handler adds both attributes and the paste handler decides which one to use and which one to remove from the operation. Finally an operation with both attributes present may temporarily exist, but such operation is never sent to the filter.

(2) A value of 0 does not crop the bitmap, positive values will move the respective border of the bitmap outside the drawing frame, negative values will move the bitmap border inside the drawing frame. Cropping attributes are interpreted differently depending on the file format:

  • OOXML: Cropping is used as percentage value. The value 100 corresponds to the total size of the drawing frame.
  • ODF: Cropping is used as absolute length in 1/100 of millimeters.

Formatting Attribute Sets

All operations that set formatting attributes will contain attribute sets. These attribute sets contain sub-objects with attributes and are mapped by attribute type. Additionally, an attribute set may contain the identifier of a style sheet referenced by a component in the document.

The attribute types supported by an attribute set are dependent on the operation containing the attribute set. An attribute set will always be carried in the attrs property of the operation.

Example: A paragraph in a text document may contain paragraph attributes, character attributes, and a reference to a paragraph style sheet. The attribute set is an object containing up to two maps with attributes: 

attrs: {
                                        styleId: "Normal",
                                        paragraph: {
                                        alignment: "right",
                                        ...
                                        },
                                        character: {
                                        fontSize: 12,
                                        ...
                                        }
                                    }

AttributeSet

The generic definition of an attribute set.

Property Data Type Default Value Description
styleId String (no style sheet) Reference to the style sheet defined by an insertStyleSheet operation. MUST NOT be used in attribute sets of insertStyleSheet operations.
type1 Object {} Map with formatting attributes supported by the attribute type1.
type2 Object {} Map with formatting attributes supported by the attribute type2.

Generic Operations Reference

This chapter defines the operations that are supported by all OX Document applications.

In general, each operation is a JSON object containing the following properties:

Property Type Default Value Description
name String required The name of the operation.
osn Integer none Operation state number, used for internal consistency checks. Documents that want to apply the operation must contain exactly this state.
opl Integer 1 Operation length, used for internal consistency checks. Default value is 1, may be larger if several operations have been merged into a single operation.
noUndo Boolean false If set to a truthy value, no undo operation is generated (used only in setAttributes operation).

noOp

A special internal operation that does nothing. It's normally used (especially Spreadsheet) to synchronize the operation state number of viewing clients.

Property Type Default Value Description
name String required noOp

setDocumentAttributes

Sets default attributes for the document and for various formatting attribute types.

Property Type Default Value Description
name String required setDocumentAttributes
attrs DocumentAttributeSet required Application dependent attribute set with default attribute values for different attribute types.

insertFontDescription

Inserts an extended description for a specific font which an be used for font substitution algorithms.

Property Type Default Value Description

Property Type Default Value Description
altNames Array<String> [] A list of alternative names for the font.
family String The font family.
pitch Enum variable The font pitch. Either fixed or variable.
panose1 Array<Integer> none The font typeface classification number. See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PANOSE.

insertStyleSheet

Inserts a new style sheet with its formatting attributes into the document.

Property Type Default Value Description

Proposals

To reduce the size of operations, and the complexity of the JSON data, color values should be sent as strings instead of structured JSON objects.

ColorStr

Description of a color value. The general structure of a color string orientates on CSS function-style color values, extended to the needs of document operations. As an alternative, an even simpler space-only syntax could be used: 

"color-type(values) [transformation-type(value) ...] [fallback(value)]"

or 

"color-type [values] [transformation-type [value] ...] [fallback value]"

Example: 

"hsl(0,100000,50000) lumMod(50000) gray fallback(CCCCCC)"

or 

"hsl 0 100000 50000 lumMod 50000 gray fallback CCCCCC"

Same color using the old JSON object style: 

{"type":"hsl","value":{"h":0,"s":100000,"l":50000},"transformations":[{"type":"lumMod","value":50000},{"type":"gray"}],"fallbackValue":"CCCCCC"}

Base Color

The first token is a description of the base color. The following color types are available:

Color Type Description Example
rgb(RRGGBB) RGB color model, 6-digits upper-case hexadecimal string. rgb(FF0000)
hsl(H,S,L) HSL color model (hue, saturation, luminance). hsl(0,100000,50000)
H Hue Integer in the interval [0,21599999] (60,000th degrees).
S Saturation Integer in the interval [0,100000] (1,000th percent).
L Luminance Integer in the interval [0,100000] (1,000th percent).
crgb(R,G,B) CRGB color model, each color channel as percentage. crgb(100000,0,0)
R Red Integer in the interval [0,100000] (1,000th percent).
G Green Integer in the interval [0,100000] (1,000th percent).
B Blue Integer in the interval [0,100000] (1,000th percent).
sch(name) Color from the color scheme of the current formatting theme. sch(accent1)
name Color name Case-sensitive name of the scheme color.
sys(name) Color from the system color scheme dependig on the current platform and browser. sys(window)
name Color name Case-sensitive name of the system color.
pre(name) Predefined color name. pre(red)
name Color name Case-sensitive name of the preset color.
auto The effective color value will be calculated from the context. auto

Automatic colors will be calculated as following:

Context Description
Text characters May depend on the current background color (character/paragraph) which must be calculated by the client.
Border lines Usually black. May be a different color, e.g. in spreadsheet documents where the automatic border color equals the grid line color.
Background fill Usually transparent, or any predefined color or calculated color depending on the context, e.g. in chart objects.

Color Transformations

The next tokens are descriptions how to transform the base color. The following variables will be used in the following descriptions:

Variable Value Range Description
R [0,100000] Red channel (RGB color model).
G [0,100000] Green channel (RGB color model).
B [0,100000] Blue channel (RGB color model).
H [0,21599999] Hue channel (HSL color model). 0: red (0deg); 7200000: green (120deg); 14400000: blue (240deg).
S [0,100000] Saturation channel (HSL color model). 0: gray; 100000: full color.
L [0,100000] Luminance channel (HSL color model). 0: black; 50000: color; 100000: white.
A [0,100000] Opacity (alpha channel). 0: transparent; 100000: opaque.

The following table will describe how to modify the components of the color for each transformation type:

Transformation Type Value Range Value Description Color Model Implementation Notes Notes
alpha(value) [0,100000] Sets the opaqueness of the color. By default, the color is fully opaque. 0: transparent; 100000: opaque. RGB/HSL Anew = value
alphaMod(value) [0,*] Modulates the opaqueness of the color. The value 100000 leaves opacity unmodified. RGB/HSL Anew = A * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,100000]
alphaOff(value) [-100000,100000] Shifts the opaqueness of the color. The value 0 leaves opacity unmodified. RGB/HSL Anew = A + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
red(value) [0,100000] Sets the red channel of the color. RGB Rnew = value
redMod(value) [0,*] Modulates the red channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Rnew = R * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,100000]
redOff(value) [-100000,100000] Shifts the red channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Rnew = R + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
green(value) [0,100000] Sets the green channel of the color. RGB Gnew = value
greenMod(value) [0,*] Modulates the green channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Gnew = G + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
greenOff(value) [-100000,100000] Shifts the green channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Gnew = G + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
blue(value) [0,100000] Sets the green channel of the color. RGB Gnew = value
blueMod(value) [0,*] Modulates the blue channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Bnew = B * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,100000]
blueOff(value) [-100000,100000] Shifts the blue channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. RGB Bnew = B + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
hue(value) [0,21599999] Sets the hue channel of the color. HSL Hnew = value
hueMod(value) [0,*] Modulates the hue channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Hnew = H * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,21599999]
hueOff(value) [-21599999,21599999] Shifts the hue channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Hnew = H + value, result restricted to interval [0,21599999]
sat(value) [0,100000] Sets the saturation channel of the color. HSL Snew = value
satMod(value) [0,*] Modulates the saturation channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Snew = S * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,100000]
satOff(value) [-100000,100000] Shifts the saturation channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Snew = S + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000]
lum(value) [0,100000] Sets the luminance channel of the color. HSL Lnew = value (1)
lumMod(value) [0,*] Modulates the luminance channel of the color. The value 100000 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Lnew = L * (value/100000), result restricted to interval [0,100000] (1)
lumOff(value) [-100000,100000] Shifts the luminance channel of the color. The value 0 leaves the channel unmodified. HSL Lnew = L + value, result restricted to interval [0,100000] (1)
shade(value) [0,100000] Darkens the color. 0: black; 100000: original color. RGB RGBnew = RGB * (value/100000) (2)
tint(value) [0,100000] Lightens the color. 0: white; 100000: original color. RGB RGBnew = (RGB-100000) * (value/100000) + 100000 (2)
comp not used Complement color (rotate hue by 180 degrees). HSL Hnew = (H + 10800000) mod 21600000
inv not used Inverse color (color channels inversed). RGB RGBnew = 100000 - RGB (2)
gamma not used Gamma correction (increases luminance of medium light colors). RGB RGBnew = (RGB/100000)1/2.27 * 100000 (2)
invGamma not used Inversed gamma correction (decreases luminance of medium light colors). RGB RGBnew = (RGB/100000)2.27 * 100000 (2)
gray not used Monochrome color. RGB RGBnew = 0.22 * R + 0.72 * G + 0.06 * B (2)

Notes:

(1) If a luminance transformation results in the luminance values 0 or 100000, additionally the saturation of the color must be set to 0.

(2) Must be applied to all three color channels R, G, and B.

Example: 

"hsl(0,100000,50000) lumMod(50000) gray"

Fallback Color

The last token may be used to provide the effective RGB color in case the target component cannot handle the complex color model but expects simple hexadecimal RGB colors.

Fallback Type Description
fallback(RRGGBB) RGB color model, 6-digits upper-case hexadecimal string.

Example: 

"pre(red) fallback(FF0000)"

Operations in OX Text Applications

This article contains definitions for additional operations for text documents, which are not described in Operations in OX Document Applications.

Most operations target specific text components (characters, paragraphs, tables, table cells, drawing objects, etc.) or ranges of text components. The following general rules apply for these operations:

  1. Single text components are addressed by a start property containing a Position array.
  2. Ranges of text components are addressed by a start and an end property, both containing a Position array. The range is inclusive, the text component addressed by end is part of the range. The end position must be equal to start or must follow start.

Data Types

ParagraphPosition

A paragraph position is an array of integers (see generic type Position) specifying the position of a paragraph in the text document.

  • Positions of paragraphs on the root level of the document consist of an array with a single integer element: the zero-based index of the paragraph among all root level text components (paragraphs, tables).
  • Positions of paragraphs inside a table cell consist of an array with a complete TableCellPosition, followed by the zero-based index of the paragraph among all text components inside the cell (paragraphs, tables).
  • Positions of paragraphs inside a drawing object consist of an array with a complete DrawingPosition, followed by the zero-based index of the paragraph among all text components inside the drawing object (paragraphs, tables).

Examples:

  • The paragraph position [1] addresses the paragraph at index 1 in the document (second paragraph, or first paragraph following a leading table).
  • The paragraph position [3, 2, 1, 0] may address the leading paragraph (index 0) inside the table cell at the position [3, 2, 1].
  • The paragraph position [0, 1, 2] may address the third paragraph (index 2) inside the drawing object at the position [0, 1].

TablePosition

A table position is an array of integers (see generic type Position) specifying the position of a table in the text document.

  • Positions of tables on the root level of the document consist of an array with a single integer element: the zero-based index of the table among all root level text components (paragraphs, tables).
  • Positions of tables inside a table cell consist of an array with a complete TableCellPosition, followed by the zero-based index of the table among all text components inside the cell (paragraphs, tables).
  • Positions of tables inside a drawing object consist of an array with a complete DrawingPosition, followed by the zero-based index of the table among all text components inside the drawing object (paragraphs, tables).

Examples:

  • The table position [1] addresses the table at index 1 in the document (second table, or first table following a leading paragraph).
  • The table position [3, 2, 1, 0] may address the leading table (index 0) inside the table cell at the position [3, 2, 1].
  • The table position [0, 1, 2] may address the third table (index 2) inside the drawing object at the position [0, 1].

TableRowPosition

A table row position is an array of integers (see generic type Position) specifying the position of a single row in a table of the text document.

  • It consists of an array of integers with a complete TablePosition, followed by the zero-based index of the table row inside the table.

Examples:

  • The table row position [1, 0] addresses the first row (index 0) inside the table at the position [1].

TableCellPosition

A table cell position is an array of integers (see generic type Position) specifying the position of a single cell in a table row of the text document.

  • It consists of an array of integers with a complete TableRowPosition, followed by the zero-based index of the table cell inside the table row.

Examples:

  • The table cell position [2, 1, 0] addresses the first cell (index 0) inside the second row (index 1) inside the table at the position [2].

CharacterPosition

A character position is an array of integers (see generic type Position) specifying the position of a single character, or another text component treated as a character (fields, tabs, drawing objects) in the text document.

  • It consists of an array of integers with a complete ParagraphPosition, followed by the zero-based index of the character among all components in the paragraph (characters, fields, tabs, drawing objects).

Examples:

  • The character position [1, 0] addresses the first character (index 0) inside the paragraph at the position [1].
  • The character position [4, 3, 2, 1, 0] addresses the first character (index 0) inside the paragraph at the position [4, 3, 2, 1] which is the second text component inside the table cell at [4, 3, 2].

DrawingPosition

The position of a drawing object in a text document. Drawings that are direct children of a paragraph are treated like characters and are CharacterPosition values. Otherwise, the drawing is embedded in another drawing object, and its position is an EmbeddedDrawingPosition value.

Examples:

  • The drawing position [1, 0] addresses the leading drawing (index 0) inside the paragraph at the position [1].
  • The drawing position [4, 3, 2, 1, 0] addresses the leading drawing (index 0) inside the paragraph at the position [4, 3, 2, 1] which is the second text component inside the table cell at [4, 3, 2].
  • The drawing position [1, 0, 0] addresses the first child drawing in the group object at position [1, 0].

TextPosition

An arbitrary position (an array of integers) of any component in a text document: one of ParagraphPosition, TablePosition, TableRowPosition, TableCellPosition, CharacterPosition, or DrawingPosition.

ChangeTrackInfo

Defines a change track object with autor, data, uid and old attributes.

Property Data Type Default Value Description
author String The change track author.
date String The date of the change track.
uid String The user id of the change track.
attrs Object {} The old element attributes, that are required, if the change track is rejected. This is only necessary for change track type modified.

Text Operations Reference

delete

Deletes a component or a range of related components.

Property Data Type Default Value Description
name String required delete
start TextPosition required The position of the first component that will be deleted.
end TextPosition value of start The position of the last component that will be deleted (closed range). if omitted, this operation addresses a single component.
target String specifies the target position, needs only to be used if document parts such as header or footer are addressed

Note: Currently, only single components can be deleted, except for text ranges in a paragraph. A text range can include characters, fields, and drawing objects, but must be contained in a single paragraph.

The operation deletes only the addressed components. It will never delete any parent components, even if they are left empty (for example: after deleting the last row in a table, the empty table will remain in the document).

move

Note: Currently, only single drawing components can be moved. The property end will not be evaluated at all.

insertHeaderFooter

Inserts Header or Footer in the document.

Property Data Type Default Value Description
name String required insertHeaderFooter
id String required Unique name, which is used as a target for operations belonging to this element
type String required Should start with header_ or footer_ to identify is it header or footer
Notes
  • Currently, three types of header/footer are supported:
  1. header_default (footer_default) - default type, used if no other type is defined or available
  2. header_first (footer_first) - if defined, used only on first page in document. Has bigger priority then _default, and overwrites it.
  3. header_even (footer_even) - if defined, used on even pages, and overwrites _default type, as it has higher priority. With this type defined, on odd pages, _default type is used.

insertRange

Inserts a range object into the document. This ranges can be used for comments or complex fields.

Property Type Default Value Description
name String required insertCommentRange
start CharacterPosition required The position where the range will be inserted. The range will be inserted before the character that is currently located at this position.
target String Specifies the target position, needs only to be used, if specific document parts like headers or footers are addressed.
id String Unique name, which is used as a target for insertComment operations
position Enum start, end start Specifies, if this is a start range marker or an end range marker.
type Enum required The type of the element using this range marker.
comment The range marker belongs to a comment.
field The range marker belongs to a complex field.
attrs CharacterAttributeSet {} Attribute set with additional character attributes.
Notes
  • OOXML: comment range is displayed only, if there is a start, end and the corresponding comment available (with matching id) otherwise the comment is represented by the position of the insertComment operation.
  • ODT: comment range is restricted by the comment node and a corresponding end node for the end of the range with the matching id.
Example (OOXML)
  • 18 E insertParagraph start:[0]
  • 19 E insertText start:[0,0],text:Hallo,
  • 20 E inserttRange start:[0,7],type:comment,position: start,id:comment_0
  • 21 E insertText start:[0,8],text:wiegeht
  • 22 E insertRange start:[0,16],type:comment,position: end,id:comment_0
  • 23 E insertComment start:[0,17],id:comment_0,author:Microsoft-Konto,date:2015-03-04T12:16:00Z
  • 24 E insertParagraph start:[0],target:comment_0,attrs:{styleId:Kommentartext}
  • 25 E insertText start:[0,0],target:comment_0,text:huhu
  • 26 E insertText start:[0,18],text:es
  • 27 E insertText start:[0,22],text:Ihnen?

splitCell

Splits a merged table cell into two or more cells.

Property Data Type Default Value Description
name String required splitCell
start TableCellPosition required The position of the cell to be split.
content Integer[] required An array containing the number of components new cells should get from the split cell. The length of this array defines the number of new cells that should be created.
gridSpan Integer[] [] An array of span values that should be applied to the cells (the cell that is addressed by position + the cells that are created). If this parameter is omitted, each cell gets a gridspan of 1. The length of this parameter must not be greater than the length of the content array + 1. (content [0] a new cell without moving content is created. content [4,0,1] creates three new cells by moving 5 components.)
target String specifies the target position, needs only to be used if document parts such as header or footer are addressed
